  "answer": "**No such passage appears in the Falsafa corpus.**\n\nDespite extensive searches for Latin terms, maxims, Roman law concepts (\"Latin\", \"maxim\", \"dominium\", \"res nullius\", \"roman law\", \"jus\", \"quirit\", \"quod\", \"accession\"), and review of relevant chapters (e.g., Vol. II Ch. 47 on jurisconsults' opinions; Ch. 48–49 on legislative definitions and Code civil critique, including \"droit d'accession\"—a Latin-derived Roman law term used in French without translation), Comte writes entirely in French. He critiques Roman jurists and terms like \"droit d'accession\" philosophically but quotes no Latin maxims and translates or explains concepts into French prose. No \"slip toward Latin\" occurs.\n\nThe corpus covers both *Traité de la propriété* vols. I–II and *Traité de législation* vols. I–IV; this detail is absent.[^1]",
